{
  "version": 2,
  "name": "Watercolor",
  "description": "Watercolor, decomposed: a feedback paint-flow simulation built from atoms. node.feedback carries last frame's accumulated paint; node.gain(decay) + node.mix(Max) form the decayed-max composite against the source; ONE node.flow_field_noise (warp-free, half-res) drives both node.uv_displace_by_flow (the fBM flow displacement) AND, via scale_offset, the node.masked_mix dilution mask; node.blur the edge diffusion; node.slope_displace the soft-light/Sobel pigment-pull; a second node.blur + node.masked_mix the flow-masked dilution that writes the feedback; node.mix(Lerp) the wet/dry composite. A node.clamp_texture guards the feedback against divergence (replacing the legacy safe_clamp). Replaces the fused 7-pass node.watercolor. Time read from FrameTime.seconds (no generator_input). Perf: the original ran the flow at reduced res with no domain warp and used a single cheap noise for the dilution mask — this graph matches that (flow_field_noise resolution=half + warp_scale=0, and the one flow texture is reused for the mask instead of a second 4-octave fBM pass). Documented deltas (visual effect, verified by eye): the flow/diffusion/luma blurs use the general atoms rather than the exact tap kernels; the dilution mask is a soft reuse of the flow field rather than an independent binary 3D-noise threshold; grain is dropped (the legacy inlined a subtle 0.15 paper-grain multiply into the composite — folding it would mean fusing, so it's omitted; node.film_grain stays in the library); the slope-displacement weight is fixed at the default rather than tracking the Displace slider; no NaN guard (decay < 1 + clamp keep it bounded).",
